title: The Map of Salt and Stars
author: Joukhadar, Zeyn*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Should the story of teenage Syrian refugees be told? A thousand times yes. But can we please have better delivery? This story was suffocated by a millShould the story of teenage Syrian refugees be told? A thousand times yes. But can we please have better delivery? This story was suffocated by a million metaphors, flowery language, long sentences, and relentless repetition. It needed to be cut in half with short, bullet-like sentences cutting through the long ones. It needed three-dimensional characters instead of types. It needed to make use of the language barrier instead of just mentioning it from time to time (see for instance, Butterfly Yellow, a YA novel also with war, human trafficking, and refugee themes) to see how language and culture can be brought to play real roles in character and plot development). Instead, the author has chosen to give readers sugary sentences that they can quote in their social media with a melodramatic effect. The best part of the book is its beautiful cover. The audiobook performance is decent too although I listened to it on 1.5-1.75 speed so as to be done with it asap. This is our book club title this month; otherwise, I would have just left it unfinished. Now I can go back to a novel that doesn’t shy away from telling pain as it really is: Strangers. ...more

I am very d**spoiler alert** The good thing about this book was that dear friends read it to me and another dear friend had translated it to Persian. I am very disappointed with how Shafak has progressed from her previous book to this one. In my opinion, up to this point, she had become better with every book. Never fulfilling her potential, but still, very promising. This time, it was a lot of fireworks, but at least for me, it didn't deliver. The first chapters were brilliant. I was expecting a lot. But soon a monotony was established. A familiar cycle of all tell, almost no show. Various narrators, but the same result. By the end of the book, you gather a lot of information about Cyprus’s natural and political history. You are also told a couple of love stories and a few family stories. It left zero impression on me. About an hour remain of the audiobook, but my book club friends who were very fond of the book told me what happens next. I’m just jotting this note down so as to remember that I tried and failed to read this book. So as to never attempt it again in case I forget the horrible experience. Gosh, this was a boring telenovela in the form of a book, a long book that made little sense, was full of melodrama, had caricatures and types for characters, was terribly sexist (no, the fact that it happened in early and mid-twenty century is no excuse), and the mystery was no mystery. I could tell from the very beginning who the “mysterious” burned-face man is. The only surprise was the incest, and that was totally, totally unnecessary. It was just there to make it more melodramatic and dark. Ugh. And don’t get me started on the artificial device of the parallels between Daniel and Julian (sorry if spellings are not right; I listened to the audiobook). The two characters are so mingled, so dependent, and so weakly developed on their own, that everyone, even those friends who had read the book several times mixed them and their life events together. So the fact that I didn't care for the two first stories obviously means that I'm also not keen on the play bringing everyone together. title: Man of My Time
author: Sofer, Dalia
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Too many mistakes in how post-revolutionary Iran and Iranians are presented. There’s also a weakness in characterization that show itself most promineToo many mistakes in how post-revolutionary Iran and Iranians are presented. There’s also a weakness in characterization that show itself most prominently in Hamid. Compare his interrogation scenes with Cromwell’s in Wolf Hall. Both are designed to show the reader that the interrogators are not wholeheartedly invested in their cruel pursuit. They’re aware that they’re doing harm. But where Mantel’s creation succeeds to charm you and win your sympathy and even admiration, Sofer’s leaves you with pity at best and more likely, as was the case with my friends and me, with repulsion. You don’t even need to compare this novel with a Booker winner. Take a look at how successfully Sabaa Tahir has presented the complex character of Elias in her YA series (book1: An Ember in the Ashes) and you’ll see what I’m talking about. And then we come to my pet peeve: this book was far too much ‘tell’ and too little ‘show’. The audiobook was performed by someone who was clearly as alien with Iran as the author. He butchered Khayyam’s quatrain, mispronounced book titles, and even managed to say the names of a few cities with the wrong pronunciation. It was at times more torture listening to him say Persian words than listen to actual mentions of torture in the book as the latter was so glossed over that a foreign reader could well come to believe that an activist in Iran would only be facing a prison sentence or in sever cases death penalty. The redeeming factor that brought about my second star was the pre-revolution content. I really enjoyed the parts that dealt with his childhood.I hope Dalia Sofer writes her next book about circumstances she is fully familiar with or at least does some extensive research before undertaking a similar project. This was a complete disappointment. ...more

review: I think this is one of those books that I should have read years ago, probably back when I read Bradbury's F451. I had the same feeling when I read AlI think this is one of those books that I should have read years ago, probably back when I read Bradbury's F451. I had the same feeling when I read Aldous Huxley's Brave New World. Everyone told me that in Foundation the ideas are great, it's just the characterisation, etc. that are weak. I know that the reason that most of the concepts in the book, in spite of their depth, don't seem that original to me is probably that Asimov's ideas have been picked up and expressed by other authors; that's why I say I should have read this book ages ago, before reading the other, arguably better novels inspired by Foundation. I like Asimov's short stories, I LOVE his non-fiction, but judging from this work, he is not a good novelist. I've been advised to read the second volume in this trilogy to see a big improvement in his storytelling skill. No way. I was bored out of my mind while listening to volume 1. No female character until almost the end of the book, and then only two derogatory minor ones. All characters are types, not 3-dimensional individuals. You can substitute one with the other. Plotlines are so similar that you can easily predict that a) there will be an argument between individuals in the next scene, b) one party will have the upper hand in power and the other in intelligence, c) the one in power seems to hold all the cards at first, d) the underdog always wins because he (yes, always a he) is so cunning and knows how people tick, e) years pass and another crisis looms near, f) go back to (a). No thanks....more

review: **spoiler alert** What a beautiful book in both form and content. Interestingly, although the author is a woman, for me the best parts belonged to Zha**spoiler alert** What a beautiful book in both form and content. Interestingly, although the author is a woman, for me the best parts belonged to Zhang Bo and Yongzong. These two didn’t need to be constantly explained and even much described; they could talk and act and you’d totally get them. They were warm and alive. Even the college boy that Liya became friends with had similar characteristics. In short, while I was equally fascinated by all characters, I felt that the male ones were more animated and real. That being said, the center of the story for me remains to be the mother and daughter and how the daughter gains more self-knowledge by trying to finally know her enigma of a mother. Also, what great timing. To read this book while I’m reading or have recently finished reading on my own or with my friends: a) Metaphors We Live By in which we discussed thinking of time as forward/behind, a movement through space, etc., b) Recursion, also dealing with the concept of time and how humanity perceives it, c) Games People Play, dealing with performance and faces we show different people among other things, and finally d)The Other Einstein, a book about Einstein’s first wife, a brilliant physicist, and her unacknowledged contribution to the theory of relativity. A final point on the audio version: The audiobook performance is also very good. ...more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: **spoiler alert** I admire this book for several reasons. Firstly, it’s one of the rare books that portray a highly educated woman in a field besides **spoiler alert** I admire this book for several reasons. Firstly, it’s one of the rare books that portray a highly educated woman in a field besides humanity or arts as being strong in character and mind as well as possessing rich empathy. Usually authors, either knowingly or inadvertently, show such women as either shallow and silly or hard and emotionless. Another thing that I love about this book is that the science is real and an organic part of the story rather than some fluff used as a prop. In this aspect, Lost and Wanted reminds me of Neel Mukherji’s The Lives of Others. Finally, I like the fact that Nell Freudenberger has accomplished the difficult task of interweaving several themes and story lines without any of them seeming out of place or inferior. The only reason that I didn’t give five stars to the book was that at times it lost its appeal and felt too long, tough It never stayed that way for more than some pages and the story would pick up again. Finally, a word about the audiobook: sometimes I listen to an audiobook with such a masterful performance that I go in search of the other books performed by the same reader, not wishing to sever the emotional tie I have established with their voice and tone after that book comes to its inevitable end. Ann Marie Lee has become one of these joys. I’m grateful to her for bringing this valuable novel to life for me. ...more

All the same, the story itself was an engaging one, which is why I finished the book. It deals with vital issues of our present world. I only wish the author refrained from turning certain characters into his mouthpiece and let the events and normal dialogue have their own effect. review: **spoiler alert** I don’t know whether it’s my fault that I’ve read too many crime novels and can guess the plot twists or if this book was too transp**spoiler alert** I don’t know whether it’s my fault that I’ve read too many crime novels and can guess the plot twists or if this book was too transparent, but I could easily guess that Maud has assumed Maggie’s identity as soon as it was mentioned that they had the same first name. Ezra being the bad guy was also more or less apparent from the fact that kind, sympathetic Mitsy (not sure of the spelling as I listened to the audiobook) hated him. I knew Mrs Warren wasn’t the killer because she was portrayed as evil, and it was quite obvious that she is the red herring. However, my main problem with the book is not that I wasn’t much surprised by the revelations. Rather, it was the overt sentimentality of the book. Ugh. The narrator lingered in Hal’s mind for too long, describing over and over and over again how she felt, how strong her grief was, how miserable she felt, how frightened and desperate she was, how guilty she felt, etc. Enough already, Ms Ware. Show us, don’t tell us, or at least tell us less. Apparently the writer is described as the modern age Agatha Christie, but if you ask me, she’s anything but. I increased the speed of the audiobook to 1.75. I couldn’t put up with the whiny atmosphere otherwise. I’m not saying the novel is hopeless. Not at all. This book could have been a really good one if it had a ruthless editor who wouldn’t be afraid of trimming it to a third of its present length. When we come out of Hal’s mind and there is some dialogue between other characters, uninterrupted by the commentary on how Hal was perceiving the conversation, things improve a lot. The plot is intriguing as well and perhaps not as transparent for one who doesn’t read a crime novel every week or so :-))...more

The most interesting aspect was that it dealt more with the survival & readjusting period than with the camp years, something that I had never seen in fiction (please let me know in the comments if there are other/better works of fiction dealing predominantly with the rehabilitation of Holocaust survivors during 1945-1948). The least attractive features were the predictability of the plot and the author's complete silence regarding the controversy of displacing and persecuting Arabs to create Israel....more

The book tries to be dystopian, but in reality it's an ordinary romance with cliche characters and affected language, peppered with a handful of environmental and political statements to give it a semblance of profundity. I'm definitely not going to listen to the next volumes. With this one, I increased the speed of the audiobook playback to get it over with as quickly as possible. An essayist because the only nice it’s of his fiction is the historical-political message he wants to convey and a script writer because you can easily transform his novels into movies without a single loss (and probably with some improvements). Those reservations aside, as a spy novel, Hydra Head has another shortcoming as well. It’s not engaging enough, or at least it wasn’t so for me. review: Thank God this is finally finished. What a long, long, long, long, tedious journey this book turned out to be for me. I am happy for all of you who haThank God this is finally finished. What a long, long, long, long, tedious journey this book turned out to be for me. I am happy for all of you who have enjoyed it and given it four and five stars, but I can’t bring myself to give it more than 2. The main problem I had (it’s so great to finally be able to talk about this book in past tense) with 4 3 2 1 wasn’t its length; I’ve read and enjoyed longer books. No, the major issue was not finding any of the four Fergusons engaging enough. In the last chapter, the Ferguson who was supposedly writing the novel said that the only way he could do justice to the novel was to love each of the three other Fergusons. I’d say the reader must feel a similar love in order to enjoy this book instead of finding it a drudgery. Sadly, I lacked the emotion. The idea behind the plot is brilliant, but a similar idea is, in my opinion, executed far more successfully in Life after Life and not only with regards to creating more lovable characters, but also in marrying history to the narrative plot. History and a study of the society appear as organic parts of the book in Life after Life, whereas in 4 3 2 1 it seems for the most part that a documentary is running in the background, separate from the events of the story. All the same, the book was not devoid of merits for me. There were parts that were beautiful and certainly quotable. However, for me, they were not as frequent as to justify going through 900+ pages. Happily, I didn’t need to. I listened to the audiobook, and the great performance plus the serene voice of the reader encouraged me to keep listening to this seemingly unending novel. ...more

review: I loved this unusual novel. I’m going to miss Selin. She is definitely a character that I would have loved to meet and befriend in real life. I also eI loved this unusual novel. I’m going to miss Selin. She is definitely a character that I would have loved to meet and befriend in real life. I also enjoyed the philosophical-linguistic aspect of this work immensely. This is I think the third or fourth book I have read in the past couple of months that have been written by Americans born to immigrants, and Asian immigrants at that (Asian in the sense of coming from the continent of Asia, not just the Far East) and that I have greatly admired. The audiobook is read by he author herself and she has done a marvelous job. Although this will certainly remain one of my favorite novels, I do not recommend it to everyone. You have to have some patience with a story that develops rather slowly and with no epic climaxes. You should want to observe how young Selin discovers truths about her personality and the world. It would certainly help if you have a passion for languages and linguistics. It certainly wouldn’t hurt if you have the same quirky sense of humor as Selin has. There were places I laughed out loud, but I’m not sure if most people would find those lines funny. I can’t wait for Elif Batuman’s next novel. ...more

review: Normally I don’t enjoy stories as much as novels, but this book is far more than a collection of stories. Apart from the common themes, the stories inNormally I don’t enjoy stories as much as novels, but this book is far more than a collection of stories. Apart from the common themes, the stories in Sour Heart relate to one another in this way that a character encountered in one story is passingly mentioned in another. It is like the grapes on the book cover: all grapes are connected in the bunch. More than anything else I have read, this book also brings home how the horrors (and sporadic joys) experienced in China after the revolution continues to have an effect on the Chinese families who have migrated to the USA. The empowering and also the suffocating force of one’s family is explored from multiple aspects, the different experiences that migrated children and parents have are beautifully delved into, and the hope and despair that they alternately go through are emphatically described. Naturally, I liked some stories less than the others, but overall it was a brilliant book. The audiobook performance was also recommendable. ...more

review: 3.65 stars to be more exact. I liked this much better than her Nightingale novel. Home Front is definitely a page turner, but it is also a tearjerker,3.65 stars to be more exact. I liked this much better than her Nightingale novel. Home Front is definitely a page turner, but it is also a tearjerker, which is always a warning sign for me. Also, there were repetitions and explanations that I could do without. I couldn't help comparing this long novel with a chapter in a book that I am reading at the moment: Let the Great World Spin. That chapter is about how the Vietnam war affects an American family, and one of the main lines in Home Front is how Iraq war affects an American family. Whereas Colum McCann's style is crisp, concise, and yet breathtaking in the way it conveys the characters' sense of loss without being in the least melodramatic, Kristin Hannah's continuous return to what has already been emphasized enough decreases the effect she could have had with a terser form. Still, I found the content, if not the form, immensely absorbing and enjoyed listening to the audiobook, as well as to the interview with the author at the end. ...more

review: Frothy, cliche, pretentious, juvenile, a complete waste of time. If it hadn't been the August book of my book club, I wouldn't have bothered going past the first chapter. The audiobook performance was difficult to stomach as well, with three readers trying to speak English with a French accent, resulting not in originality and a native feel, but in distasteful affectation. I couldn't empathize with any of the characters, and their problems seemed extremely superficial, for which I blame the author because I firmly believe that all sorrows are worth our understanding and sympathy; they should only be presented correctly, and Nina George certainly failed in this task in my opinion. All the sugary tag-lines that were inserted as if the reader was expected to rush for a pencil to underline them were weak echos of sentiments far better expressed by Rumi, Khayyam, Hafiz, Shakespeare, Wordsworth, Keats, etc. I was very disappointed with this book....more

review: **spoiler alert** Not at all an easy read; in fact at points I got so grossed out that I had to stop the audiobook and listen to Simply Clean, a book **spoiler alert** Not at all an easy read; in fact at points I got so grossed out that I had to stop the audiobook and listen to Simply Clean, a book on keeping a clean household, just to purge my mind :-)) However, my perseverance paid off and I soon became invested in the main character, who is also the narrator of the story. She is -- or rather was at the age of 24 because she is now an old woman and apparently an altogether different person -- rather unlikeable but still very understandable. It is easy to feel compassion for Eileen, to wish her a better life, but it is difficult to enjoy her company, to listen to her detailed descriptions of her various physical obsessions. Yet the author has masterfully created and maintained a Poe-like atmosphere, a fascinatingly believable character in spite of her oddities, and a delicate balance, in my opinion, between the aversion created in the reader and the desire to learn what Eileen will become. For me the most redemptive part of the story was the contrast between Eileen's reaction to Mrs. Polk's confession and Rebecca's attitude in finding that she has missed out on it. All in all, I loved the book; just don't ask me to listen to anything so dark and heavy for at least a month :-))...more

review: I had very mixed feelings as I went through this book. There were gems that I cherished and there were parts that left me disgusted. I wonder if my stI had very mixed feelings as I went through this book. There were gems that I cherished and there were parts that left me disgusted. It's a page-turner, at least for the first three quarters of the book, and the two plots are nicely balanced and developed, but it suffers from repetition and unnecessary fillers. It could have benefited from some ruthless editing. Also, apart from the brief pause on the role Julia had played in the distance created between her and Bertrand, the fault is constantly laid on the husband. I find it hard to believe that a person like Julia wouldn't feel more responsible, more guilty, about her part, where she is so eager, so desperate to apologize for her in-law's behavior sixty years ago to Sarah's son. I should also mention that I particularly liked that the contemporary plot was added so deftly from the beginning, rather than the awkward, artificial way it was done in Nightingale. All in all, one of the better novels about the occupied France and the Holocaust. review: I read this masterpiece for the first time in Persian when I was in my late teens and fell in love with it right away. I would re-read my favorite pasI read this masterpiece for the first time in Persian when I was in my late teens and fell in love with it right away. This time I listened to the English audiobook, experiencing the novel not only in a different language and medium, but also from the altered perspective of a middle-aged adult. I still love the plot. My favorite scenes remain more or less the same. I still find Tolstoy's philosophizing about the role of providence rather uninteresting, though I feel less forgiving about it. Surprisingly, however, one of the main characters has lost all his charm for me: Pierre. I think if I had revised War and Peace 30 years ago, I'd have given it five stars.
